We can now produce the damage curves for each study. As it can be seen, the relationship can be adequately described by a straight line.


::: {.cell hash='yieldloss-concepts_cache/html/fig-damagecurve1_d5774c95da3f5c4a02eecdbea1fd8eeb'}

```{.r .cell-code}
wm2 |> 
  ggplot(aes(inc, yld, 
             group = study))+
  geom_point(size = 2)+
   theme_r4pde(font_size= 14)+
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = F, color = "black", fullrange = T)+
  ylim(1800, 3500)+
  facet_wrap(~study)+
  labs(x = "White mold incidence (%)",
       y = "Soybean yield (kg/ha)",
       color = "Study")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![Relationship between soybean yield and incidence of white mold in two experiments](yieldloss-concepts_files/figure-html/fig-damagecurve1-1.png){#fig-damagecurve1 width=672}
:::
:::


We can plot the relationships for all studies combined, which will resemble a "spaghetti" plot after adding the individual regression lines.


::: {.cell hash='yieldloss-concepts_cache/html/fig-damagecurve2_3aba4b3313b72989156fb791979b19e1'}

```{.r .cell-code}
p1 <- wm |> 
  ggplot(aes(inc, yld, group = study))+
  theme_r4pde(font_size = 14)+
  geom_point(size = 2, alpha = 0.5)+
  ylim(0, 5000)+
  labs(x = "White mold incidence (%)",
       y = "Soybean yield (kg/ha)")

p2 <- wm |> 
  ggplot(aes(inc, yld, group = study))+
  theme_r4pde(font_size = 14)+
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = F, fullrange = T, color = "black")+
  ylim(0, 5000)+
  labs(x = "White mold incidence (%)",
       y = "Soybean yield (kg/ha)")

library(patchwork)
p1 | p2
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![Relationship between soybean yield and incidence of white mold across trials. Observed (left) and fitted regression lines (right)](yieldloss-concepts_files/figure-html/fig-damagecurve2-1.png){#fig-damagecurve2 width=672}
:::
:::
